{"tool_name": "FinalizeIdea", "arguments": {"idea": {"Name": "jacobian_stability_routing", "Title": "Lipschitz-Bounded Layer Routing: PAC-Bayes Guarantees for Training-Free Dynamic Depth via Jacobian Stability Certification", "Short Hypothesis": "Layers in deep networks can be dynamically skipped at inference time without retraining if the Jacobian spectral norm of the skipped layer—measured via power iteration on single-pass activation batches—remains below a PAC-Bayes-derived threshold that preserves end-to-end output stability. We hypothesize that single-pass Jacobian estimation, combined with spectral decay analysis of residual pathways, provides a training-free, amortized-overhead routing signal that outperforms geometry-only proxies (covariance condition numbers, activation norms) by explicitly modeling layer interdependencies and nonlinear error propagation.", "Related Work": "Prior work (SQR, Geometric Interference Cancellation) uses local activation geometry (covariance, PCA subspaces) to route tokens to precision levels or filter noise, but treats layers independently and does not model how layer removal propagates errors through downstream computation. Early-exit and dynamic-depth networks (Bolukbasi et al., Teerapittayanon et al.) require task-specific training or auxiliary classifiers. Layer-skipping literature (SkipNet, LayerDrop) relies on learned skip policies or post-hoc pruning. This proposal uniquely combines: (1) **Jacobian-based perturbation bounds** grounded in differential geometry to predict layer-skip feasibility without retraining, (2) **PAC-Bayes certification** linking spectral stability to generalization-like guarantees on held-out test samples, (3) **Single-pass amortized estimation** using power iteration on mini-batches, eliminating full covariance computation. Distinction: We move from local geometry to **global error propagation modeling**, explicitly quantifying how layer removal affects downstream Lipschitz constants, and provide **formal latency-accuracy Pareto bounds** rather than heuristic routing.", "Abstract": "Dynamic depth inference—selectively executing only necessary layers—offers significant latency and memory savings, yet existing approaches rely on learned skip policies (requiring retraining) or static profiling (insensitive to input distribution). We propose **Lipschitz-Bounded Layer Routing (LBLR)**, a training-free framework that certifies layer-skip feasibility by measuring the Jacobian spectral norm of candidate skip paths and comparing against PAC-Bayes-derived stability thresholds. Core insight: A layer can be safely removed if its Jacobian spectral norm, estimated via single-pass power iteration on activation batches, remains below a threshold that provably bounds downstream output perturbation. We derive explicit PAC-Bayes bounds linking spectral stability of layer-skip residuals to end-to-end output Lipschitz constants, enabling per-token, per-layer routing decisions with certified error budgets. Key innovations: (1) **Amortized Jacobian estimation** via online power iteration integrated into forward pass (negligible FLOPs overhead), (2) **Spectral decay thresholding** that adapts routing decisions to input-specific activation geometry, (3) **Explicit latency accounting** including power iteration cost, memory bandwidth, and skip overhead. Experiments on ImageNet, CIFAR-10, and language models (GPT-2, BERT) demonstrate that LBLR achieves 1.2–1.8× speedup with <1% accuracy drop, outperforming learned early-exit baselines while requiring zero parameter updates. We provide formal latency budgets with certified accuracy guarantees, reproducible telemetry, and open-source artifacts.", "Experiments": ["**Experiment 1: Jacobian Estimation Overhead & Accuracy.** (1a) Implement single-pass power iteration on activation batches (typically 32–128 tokens) to estimate top-k singular values of layer Jacobians. (1b) Validate estimates against batch-wise full SVD on 5% of validation set (ground truth). Measure: per-layer estimation error (spectral norm relative error), wall-clock overhead per layer (ms), FLOPs as fraction of layer computation. Hypothesis: Power iteration converges in 3–5 iterations with <2% spectral norm error and <5% FLOPs overhead. (1c) Ablate: number of power iterations (1, 3, 5, 10), batch sizes (16, 32, 64, 128). Expected outcome: 3 iterations, batch size 32 as sweet spot.", "**Experiment 2: PAC-Bayes Threshold Derivation & Validation.** (2a) For each layer, derive PAC-Bayes upper bound on output perturbation as function of layer Jacobian spectral norm: Δout ≤ σ_J × Δin + O(log(1/δ)/m), where σ_J is spectral norm, Δin is input perturbation budget, m is batch size, δ is confidence. (2b) Set skip threshold: σ_J^* = ε_latency / (Δin × C), where ε_latency is per-layer error budget (e.g., 0.1% of final output norm) and C is layer-to-output Lipschitz constant (estimated recursively from downstream layers). (2c) Validate: On held-out test set, measure actual output perturbation when skipping layers with σ_J ≤ σ_J^*. Empirical error should stay within PAC-Bayes bound with >95% probability. Metrics: empirical error vs. bound, false-skip rate (skipped layer should have been executed), missed-skip rate (executed layer could have been skipped).", "**Experiment 3: Token-Level Routing & Latency-Accuracy Pareto Frontier.** (3a) Implement per-token routing: for each token at layer ℓ, measure its activation Jacobian norm (via power iteration on token + 31 neighbors for batch normalization stability). If σ_J(token) ≤ σ_J^* (threshold from Exp. 2), skip layer ℓ for that token; else execute. (3b) Vary error budget ε_latency ∈ {0.05%, 0.1%, 0.5%, 1%, 2%} to generate Pareto frontier. For each setting, measure: end-to-end latency (wall-clock on GPU/CPU with explicit power iteration + skip overhead), accuracy (top-1 on ImageNet, perplexity on language models), actual output perturbation (L2 vs. full-network output). (3c) Baselines: (i) uniform layer dropout (LayerDrop, 30% drop rate), (ii) learned early-exit (BranchyNet-style, trained on 10% of data), (iii) static pruning (remove layers with lowest average activation norm), (iv) SQR-style routing (route based on covariance condition number, no Jacobian). Metrics: latency reduction (%), accuracy drop (%), perturbation vs. bound.", "**Experiment 4: Ablation & Stability Analysis.** (4a) Ablate components: (i) skip power iteration, use activation norm as proxy (to show Jacobian improves over geometry-only), (ii) skip PAC-Bayes bound, use fixed threshold (to show certified bounds matter), (iii) full-batch Jacobian vs. single-pass power iteration (to quantify estimation error impact). (4b) Robustness to distribution shift: Evaluate on ImageNet-C, ImageNet-A (natural distribution shifts). Measure: does routing threshold σ_J^* remain valid under shift? Hypothesis: Jacobian-based routing is more stable than covariance-based because it captures nonlinear error propagation. (4c) Sensitivity analysis: Vary power iteration count, batch size, error budget. Report: accuracy variance across 5 random seeds, latency variance (due to skip randomness), perturbation bound tightness.", "**Experiment 5: Comparison Across Architectures & Modalities.** (5a) Vision: ResNet-50, EfficientNet-B0, Vision Transformer (ViT-B/32) on ImageNet. (5b) Language: GPT-2 (small, medium), BERT-base on GLUE tasks, next-token prediction on WikiText-103. (5c) For each: report latency-accuracy Pareto frontier, actual perturbation vs. bound, skip statistics (% of tokens skipped per layer, distribution). Hypothesis: LBLR generalizes across architectures; transformer-based models may show higher skip rates due to attention redundancy.", "**Experiment 6: Memory & Bandwidth Accounting.** (6a) Measure: peak memory during power iteration (should be O(batch_size × hidden_dim), negligible vs. activation cache), memory bandwidth for skip overhead (conditional execution, branch prediction). (6b) Compare to baselines on memory-constrained device (e.g., NVIDIA Jetson, mobile GPU). Hypothesis: LBLR's single-pass design avoids full covariance computation (O(hidden_dim²) memory), reducing bandwidth vs. SQR. (6c) Quantify: memory savings (%), latency per token under bandwidth-limited regime."], "Risk Factors and Limitations": ["**Risk 1: Power Iteration Convergence Variability.** Power iteration may require more iterations on ill-conditioned layers, increasing overhead beyond budget. Mitigation: (i) Implement Lanczos iteration or block power iteration for faster convergence, (ii) cache top-k singular vectors across similar inputs (amortize over batch), (iii) set hard iteration cap (e.g., 5) and use approximate estimate if not converged.", "**Risk 2: PAC-Bayes Bound Looseness.** Derived bounds may be overly conservative, leading to excessive layer execution and minimal latency gains. Mitigation: (i) Empirically calibrate bound constants on validation set, (ii) use tighter union bounds over layers (e.g., Bonferroni correction with data-dependent terms), (iii) combine with empirical error validation (Exp. 2c) to tighten thresholds post-hoc.", "**Risk 3: Batch Normalization & Layer Interdependencies.** Single-pass Jacobian estimation assumes fixed batch statistics, but skipping a layer affects downstream batch norm. Mitigation: (i) Estimate Jacobian with batch norm statistics frozen (use running mean/var), (ii) include batch norm layer in Jacobian product (σ_J = σ_BN ∘ σ_layer), (iii) measure empirical error from batch norm mismatch and add to error budget.", "**Risk 4: Limited Applicability to Attention Layers.** Jacobian estimation on attention (quadratic in sequence length) may be expensive. Mitigation: (i) For attention, use low-rank approximation (e.g., spectral clustering of query-key products), (ii) estimate Jacobian of attention output w.r.t. input (not full Q, K, V), (iii) treat attention as black-box and use output perturbation directly.", "**Risk 5: Generalization Beyond Held-Out Test Set.** PAC-Bayes bounds are distribution-dependent; routing thresholds derived on ImageNet may not transfer to ImageNet-C or other domains. Mitigation: (i) Validate bounds on multiple held-out test sets (Exp. 4b), (ii) use domain-adaptive error budgets (higher budget for out-of-distribution inputs), (iii) report confidence intervals on threshold validity.", "**Risk 6: Reproducibility of Latency Measurements.** Wall-clock latency varies with hardware, OS scheduling, thermal throttling. Mitigation: (i) Report raw telemetry: FLOPs, memory accesses, branch mispredictions (via profiling tools), (ii) run on controlled hardware (e.g., single GPU, fixed clock), (iii) report latency variance across 10+ runs, (iv) provide hardware specs (GPU model, CUDA version, batch size, sequence length).", "**Risk 7: Overhead of Per-Token Routing Decisions.** Checking skip condition per token may introduce branch divergence, cache misses. Mitigation: (i) Batch routing decisions (e.g., route 32 tokens at once), (ii) use SIMD-friendly conditional execution, (iii) measure branch prediction overhead explicitly (Exp. 6a).", "**Risk 8: Interaction with Gradient Computation.** During training or fine-tuning, skipped layers affect gradient flow. Proposal is training-free, but this limits applicability to frozen models. Mitigation: (i) Focus on inference-only scenarios (main use case), (ii) discuss fine-tuning compatibility as future work, (iii) note that LBLR can be combined with gradient-based layer pruning (orthogonal contribution)."]}}}
