arying hyperparameters by ±50%']}, {'name': 'Mechanistic Analysis: Spectral Signatures vs. Layer Function', 'description': "Investigate whether spectral signatures correlate with known layer functions in transformers. Categorize layers: (1) attention layers (self-attention projections); (2) MLP layers (feed-forward networks); (3) normalization layers. For each category, compute mean/std of spectral metrics (α, κ, r_eff). Hypothesis: attention layers have higher κ and lower α (slower decay) than MLP layers, reflecting their role in capturing long-range dependencies. Visualize: (1) heatmap of κ across layers; (2) scatter plot (α vs. κ) colored by layer type; (3) correlation matrix between spectral metrics and layer type (via Cramér's V or mutual information). Validate by checking if human-interpretable layer functions align with precision assignments.", 'metrics': ['Mean/std of α, κ, r_eff per layer type', 'Pearson/Spearman correlation between spectral metrics and layer type', 'Visualization quality: clarity of layer type clustering in spectral space', 'Percentage of attention layers assigned higher precision than MLP layers']}, {'name': 'Multi-Seed Reproducibility and Confidence Intervals', 'description': 'Run full pipeline (diagnostics + routing + inference) on 10 independent random seeds (if applicable, e.g., different model initializations or validation set splits). Measure: (1) variance in precision map (% of layers with identical assignments across seeds); (2) variance in accuracy; (3) variance in latency. Compute 95% confidence intervals for all metrics. Hypothesis: deterministic routing produces identical precision maps and negligible variance in accuracy/latency across seeds.', 'metrics': ['Precision map consistency (% identical across 10 seeds)', 'Accuracy variance (std, 95% CI)', 'Latency variance (std, 95% CI)', 'Percentage of metrics where CI width < 1% of mean value']}], 'Risk Factors and Limitations': [{'risk': 'Spectral metrics may not fully capture layer sensitivity. Weight Hessian is a proxy for true loss landscape curvature; if layers exhibit highly nonlinear behavior or contain skip connections, spectral analysis of weights alone may miss important interactions.', 'mitigation': 'Validate correlation between spectral metrics and empirical sensitivity (gradient perturbation) in Exp. 1. If correlation is weak (r < 0.7), incorporate additional diagnostics (e.g., Fisher information matrix, attention entropy). Explicitly quantify this limitation in results.'}, {'risk': 'PAC-Bayes bounds may be loose, leading to overly conservative precision assignments. If bounds are too conservative, the method may assign higher precision than necessary, reducing efficiency gains.', 'mitigation': 'In Exp. 3, measure bound tightness. If empirical generalization gaps are consistently <50% of predicted bounds, investigate tighter PAC-Bayes variants or data-dependent bounds. Report tightness as a limitation.'}, {'risk': 'SVD computation may be expensive for very large models. While SVD is O(d^2 · min(d_out, d_in)) per layer, for billion-parameter models this could exceed budget.', 'mitigation': 'In Exp. 4, explicitly measure SVD cost. If it exceeds 30 min for Llama-2-7B, implement low-rank SVD approximation (e.g., randomized SVD, Nyström approximation) to reduce cost to <5 min. Document trade-off between diagnostic accuracy and computational cost.'}, {'risk': 'Precision routing may not account for data-dependent effects (e.g., adversarial robustness, out-of-distribution generalization). Training-free approach may miss layer-specific vulnerabilities that only manifest on certain input distributions.', 'mitigation': 'Scope experiments to standard accuracy on in-distribution data (ImageNet, WikiText). Explicitly note in limitations that method does not optimize for robustness or OOD generalization. Suggest future work on data-dependent refinements.'}, {'risk': 'Block-level precision (per-layer) may be too coarse. Some layers may benefit from finer-grained precision (e.g., per-head or per-block precision in MLP layers).', 'mitigation': 'Enforce coarse-grained routing as design choice to maintain computational feasibility and reproducibility. If results show significant accuracy loss, conduct post-hoc analysis to identify layers where finer granularity would help. Document this as a limitation and design trade-off.'}, {'risk': 'Generalization of routing across different model sizes or architectures. Precision map learned on ViT-B may not transfer to ViT-L or different architectures (CNNs, RNNs).', 'mitigation': 'Test on multiple architectures (ViT variants, Llama variants, potentially BERT). If transfer is poor, investigate whether spectral signatures scale predictably with model size/architecture. Report transfer success rates and identify failure modes.'}, {'risk': 'Comparison fairness: BRECQ and OCS may benefit from task-specific tuning or calibration data selection. Our method uses only frozen weights, which is inherently limited.', 'mitigation': "Ensure fair comparison: (1) use same calibration data/hyperparameters for all baselines; (2) report computational cost of calibration explicitly; (3) highlight that our method's advantage is in computational efficiency, not necessarily accuracy. Position as complementary approach for scenarios where calibration is infeasible."}, {'risk': 'Precision routing may not generalize to dynamic/adaptive inference (e.g., token pruning, early exit). Method assumes static precision assignment.', 'mitigation': 'Scope to static inference. Note that dynamic methods require different analysis (e.g., token-level routing). Suggest future work on integration with dynamic strategies.'}, {'risk': 'Numerical stability of SVD on ill-conditioned weight matrices. If condition numbers are extremely large (κ > 1e6), SVD may suffer from numerical errors.', 'mitigation': 'In Exp. 2, monitor numerical stability: (1) compute SVD using stable algorithms (e.g., scipy.linalg.svd with full_matrices=False); (2) check for NaN/Inf in singular values; (3) report percentage of layers with κ > 1e5. If instability occurs, document and investigate alternative diagnostics (e.g., randomized SVD, Lanczos iteration).'}]}
